<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-089-342  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 089 342.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Jan 22 1990 n351 p125(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technology benefits: asking tough questions of CAD enthusiasts.andO;(cost-benefit research on computer-aided design and computer-aidedmanufacturing)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Staff engineer Don Davis of Philip-Morris is researching if moneyinvested in CAD/CAM systems has proven to be an intelligentinvestment.andP;  The answer is not clear.andP;  Specifically, Davis isexamining how large corporations deploy enterprise-wide automateddesign systems.andP;  Davis says that analyzing the costs and benefitsof CAD/CAM implementation is difficult, in part because largecorporations are reluctant to discuss their CAD/CAM experiences.andO;Davis' preliminary finding is that CAD/CAM investments have notalways cut costs.andP;  Davis suggests that companies consideringimplementing CAD/CAM should look conceptually at the entireprocess to be automated and avoid automating existing operationsthat are inefficient.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignCost Benefit AnalysisCAD-CAMAutomationGuidelines.andO;Person:    Davis, Don (research).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>